%text \textbf{Roster is just another word for a list.}
So, when you \underline\text{list} out all the elements of a set, then you are expressing the set in \underline{\text{Roster notation}}.
But if instead you list the \underline\text{conditions} that the elements of a set must satisfy, then you're using the \underline\text{Set builder notation}. %

\begin{align}
				x^2+7x+10 &= 0\implies (x+2)\cdot (x+5) = 0 \\
				\implies x &= -2, -5
				\end{align} 
%text


\textbf{But don't forget the second condition!}
Neither of $x=-2$ nor $x=-5 \in\mathbb{N}.

Hence, C is an empty set. That is, \underline{$C = \phi$}.
